rComments: All exams are essay questions and based on slides, although grading for these exams are unclear. Write as much as you can and you'll do well pretty much. He's also a very nice guy.

Solid professor, powerpoints are clear and concise and lectures are interesting! Textbook is rarely used, and he posts past tests and exams. You will see a lot of similar questions on your own test and exam! He makes you attend class because he does not post the answers to the discussion questions, which appear on tests.
There for you when you need help.

He is a great professor but his lectures are very long and the material very dense (50+slides per class). If you want to do really well, I recommend you review each class after class and then go ask questions. The midterm exam was tough, but the final exam was better.
Amazing prof!
Lectures can sometimes be boring but he is very clear and organized. His slides are very useful for midterm/final, some memorization is needed though.
Great lecturer!

Smart and kind guy. Knows his stuff and very helpful.  The class is not very engaging and the teaching methods are not progressive or varied. I find it weird that he refuses to answer questions during the break but I understand why.
the material is 'easy' but doing well in it is hard. he makes you regurgitate stupid statistics to do well. basically, if you enjoy higher level thinking and hate rote memorization, stay away

Really good prof, clearly explains material. Although would suggest you go to class regularly because there is a lot more he mentions than what is written on his slides. Tests are all essay questions and just going to class and listening will really help. Exam is not very tough if you can memorise. Take the course if the material interests you.

I liked his teaching but not the unhelpful test answer sheet he provided on his website.  A prof should post clear, concise test solutions on his/her website, and/or distribute such solutions in class, like all other U of T profs I've had.  Finally, there should be more emphasis on international economics e.g. flax taxes, EU internal migration.

Loved this class, very straightforward material and he presented it in a clear, concise material. He does write practically everything down, but he writes FAST, so it doesn't waste time or anything. I really enjoyed his class, would take it again. Dresses very typical for a univ prof - tweed jackets anyone?
excellent prof, notes on website b4 lectures, easy to follow, however, lots to memorize before tests. not hard to get a good mark if memorize everything
The class was easy to follow, straight off the lecture notes, i felt that he didnt have any real experience so he taught strictly from theory.

I found that Prof. Reid was able to make this an interesting and informative course.  He was always available to talk to and stayed after class to answer questions.  After getting a 71% on the midterm, the TAs and prof were available to tell me what I needed to do to do better.  Got an 82% overall.

He is a really nice guy and pleasent to talk to.  The course material is really boring tho, and it is very hard to get a good mark in his course.  He is an effective university lecturer...his overheads were helpful when it came time to study.

Not a particularly exciting lecture to attend, mainly due to dry course material. Study from the lecture notes! All test material (pure short-answer) will be drawn from them, making textbook pretty useless. Occasionally uses poor (i.e. confusing) examples to illustrate points, but gets the job done.

This guy was smart- but not a great lecturer. The course was boring to begin with though- so I feel for him. The grading was ridiculous. Hard to get a good mark because there was so much info- hard to do better than 75%

tended to spoon feed students by writing down absolutely everything on the board, that meant that most students had the same anwsers and viewpoints which resulted in a small distribution of grades (70-72). good prof all in all. hes got huge shoulders!
Nice guy, clear lectures, good notes.  His TA is a typical UT no-speak-engrish dumbarse marker tho
Very tough to do well. Grades have a very small distribution around 70-72. The course is interesting but the grading is frustrating.
